        "initialize_peak_buffers",
        "compute_initial_detection_threshold",
        "detect_qrs_candidates",
        "refine_rpeaks_in_raw_signal"
      ],
      "depth": 1,
      "type_signature": "(signal: 1-D array of ECG amplitude samples, sampling_rate: positive integer or float (Hz)) -> 1-D array of integer sample indices marking detected R-peaks",
      "matched_primitive": null,
      "primitive_binding_confidence": 0.0,
      "primitive_binding_source": "",
      "is_optional": false,
      "is_opaque": false,
      "is_external": false,
      "parallelizable": false,
      "conceptual_summary": "threshold_adaptive_local_extremum_detector. Scans a uniformly-sampled 1-D scalar time-series and applies a multi-stage, adaptive thresholding pipeline \u2014 combining derivative-based slope analysis, moving-window energy estimation, and refractory blanking \u2014 to isolate the sample indices of dominant, periodically-recurring amplitude extrema. The algorithm dynamically updates its decision thresholds based on a running estimate of signal and noise levels, making it robust to slow baseline drift and amplitude non-stationarity. The result is a sparse index set representing the discrete-time positions of structurally salient, high-curvature transient events within the continuous waveform.. Applications: Seismology \u2014 detecting P-wave or S-wave onset indices in a continuous ground-motion velocity time-series recorded at a fixed sampling rate, where transient high-energy bursts must be isolated from a noisy, slowly-drifting baseline, Industrial condition monitoring \u2014 localising impulse-type mechanical shock events (e.g., bearing fault strike instants) in a uniformly-sampled vibration accelerometer stream, where the inter-event refractory logic prevents multiple triggers from a single impact ringdown, Neuroscience / electrophysiology \u2014 extracting action-potential spike times from an extracellular multi-unit recording array, where adaptive thresholding accommodates electrode impedance drift and varying unit amplitudes across a long recording session, Radar / sonar pulse detection \u2014 identifying the sample-level arrival times of dominant echo returns in a range-time amplitude scan, where adaptive noise-floor estimation suppresses clutter and the blanking interval prevents range-sidelobe false alarms after each primary return",
      "critic_notes": "",
      "decomposition_rationale": ""
    },
